<H2><A accessKey=3D1 href=3D"http://blog.ctrlbreak.co.uk/">Our word is =
our=20
weapon</A></H2><SPAN class=3Ddescription>A website about development,=20
globalisation and the transformation of public power. And, increasingly, =
about=20
social policy in general and housing in particular. Oh, and pictures of=20
kittens.</SPAN> </DIV>
<DIV class=3Dcontent>
<DIV id=3Dmenu>
<P align=3Dcenter><A =
href=3D"http://blog.ctrlbreak.co.uk/archives/000311.html">=AB Q=20
&amp; A on Trade &amp; Development</A> | <A=20
href=3D"http://blog.ctrlbreak.co.uk/">Main</A> | <A=20
href=3D"http://blog.ctrlbreak.co.uk/archives/000313.html">Why economists =
shouldn't=20
oppose fair trade =BB</A> </P></DIV>
<H2 class=3Ddate>May 01, 2005</H2>
<H2 class=3Dtitle>Ghana</H2>
<P>In the debate here in the UK over trade justice versus free trade, it =
looks=20
like Ghana has become everyone's favourite hobby-horse. Our pals at the=20
Globalization Institute seem particularly keen on selling Ghana as a=20
liberalisation <A=20
href=3D"http://www.globalizationinstitute.org/blog/000303.php">success =
story</A>.=20
Just how accurate is this?</P>
<P>Let's start with some basic facts. Contrary to what the GI <A=20
href=3D"http://www.globalizationinstitute.org/blog/000276.php">seems to=20
believe</A>, Ghana has not been growing "faster than any other West =
African=20
country", as a glance at the very <A=20
href=3D"http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/africa/4447773.stm">IMF =
statistics</A>=20
they base this claim on will tell you. But they are right to point out =
that=20
poverty in Ghana has fallen since the early 1990s, as <A=20
href=3D"http://www.dfid.gov.uk/pubs/files/oppgghana.pdf">this</A> recent =
DFID=20
paper points out. What doesn't get mentioned is that while Ghana has =
indeed been=20
growing steadily (but slowly) over the last twenty years, this came =
after a=20
cataclysmic recession in the early 1980s, and per capita incomes have =
yet to=20
return to the levels of the early 1970s. That DFID paper also points =
out, again=20
contrary to what the GI seems to <A=20
href=3D"http://www.globalizationinstitute.org/blog/000303.php">believe</A=
>, that=20
inequality has risen. This is very important, as it means that the =
incomes of=20
the well-off have been rising faster than those of the poor, with the =
incomes of=20
the bottom 20% growing by less than 2% a year (see chart below).</P>
<P><IMG height=3D362 alt=3Dghanappgr.png=20
src=3D"http://blog.ctrlbreak.co.uk/archives/ghanappgr.png" =
width=3D498></P>
<P>So it shouldn't be that surprising that poverty in Ghana has not =
fallen=20
across the board. Indeed, only two out of Ghana's ten regions have =
actually seen=20
statistically significant poverty reduction since 1991/92 (p. 18 of the =
<A=20
href=3D"http://www.dfid.gov.uk/pubs/files/oppgghana.pdf">DFID =
report</A>). The=20
picture is even worse if you look at the qualitative evidence: according =
to the=20
DFID researchers, <BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>there was a widely held perception that poverty levels had=20
  worsened ... Urban communities considered that the initially =
beneficial=20
  effects of economic reform in the 1980s had not been sustained, while =
rural=20
  communities felt that the vulnerability of their livelihoods was =
increasing. A=20
  similar perception of living standards having worsened, this time over =
the=20
  last decade, was also reported by communities in the Voices of the =
Poor study=20
  conducted in 1999.</BLOCKQUOTE>
<P></P>
<P>These subjective accounts may be picking up something that snapshots =
of=20
absolute poverty cannot measure - an increase in social and economic =
insecurity=20
and vulnerability. As <A=20
href=3D"http://www.utdt.edu/~redpobreza/papers_2002/Cruces.pdf">Guillermo=
=20
Cruces</A> says, there is a <I>dis</I>utility to income instability, and =
if=20
liberalisation in Ghana has caused an increase in instability, then the=20
'risk-adjusted' incomes of ordinary Ghanaians may on average be even =
lower than=20
before. </P>
<P>Still, some growth and poverty reduction is better than none. What =
can we say=20
about the causes of Ghana's recent growth? <A=20
href=3D"http://www.globalizationinstitute.org/blog/000314.php">Here</A>, =
Alex=20
Singleton of the GI is unequivocal - it's liberalisation (undefined, =
unmeasured)=20
what done it. But this ignores the aid that the DFID paper he quotes =
cites as a=20
major factor, propping up public investment to counter-act the =
"contraction of=20
wage employment opportunities". And while the DFID paper mentions the=20
remittances (monetary transfers from Ghanaian emigrants), it doesn't =
mention=20
that they've rocketed in recent years, up to 13% of GDP from only 2% in =
1990=20
according to <A href=3D"http://www.g24.org/Addison.pdf">this</A> paper, =
which=20
makes you wonder how Ghana would have done without such a boost.</P>
<P>Unevenly spread growth, heavily dependent on overseas finance - Ghana =
is=20
hardly a shining example of the glories of liberalisation. Indeed, the =
authors=20
of the DFID paper are worried:<BR>
<BLOCKQUOTE>There are though important questions about the =
sustainability of=20
  this moderate rate of progress, due to various factors including =
fiscal=20
  constraints, increases in inequality, increasing levels of domestic =
debt, and=20
  the fact that many of the benefits of the revitalisation of the cocoa =
sector=20
  may already have been realised. Future poverty reduction may be harder =
to=20
  achieve. </BLOCKQUOTE>
<P></P>
<P>The main reason Ghana has come to prominence in the last few weeks is =
the <A=20
href=3D"http://allafrica.com/stories/200504180517.html">re-ignition</A> =
of a=20
two-years-old debate about tariffs on imports on rice and poultry which =
the=20
parliament agreed to impose, only for the executive to repeal=20
(unconstitutionally, some say) after pressure from the IMF and World =
Bank. When=20
the singer Chris Martin (speaking for Oxfam) pointed out the injustice =
of=20
Ghanaian farmers put out of business by imports of heavily subsidised =
rice from=20
Europe and the US, Alex of the GI responded that "Mr Martin's =
protectionism=20
might seem a way of fighting poverty: in practice it would cause the =
poorest to=20
starve". I wonder whether the sudden huge loss of income for many rice =
farmer=20
households is more likely to bring on starvation than a rise in the =
price -=20
after all, it's not like rice is the only food available, but for many =
farmers=20
it is the only product they have ever produced. Ghana was once a net =
exporter of=20
rice, but the cut-backs under structural adjustment mean that government =

subsidies for farm equipment have dried up, making it doubly difficult =
to=20
compete with heavily subsidised imports from rich countries, which have =
<A=20
href=3D"http://www.fao.org/es/ess/compendium_2004/pdf/ESS_GHA.pdf">shot =
up in=20
recent years</A> . </P>
<P>While many producers are losing out, in the short run some families =
no doubt=20
benefit from cheap rice - but the subsidies won't last forever, and when =
they do=20
end there may be no indigenous rice sector left to pick up the slack. =
And isn't=20
Alex's celebration of subsidised rice is particularly odd given his =
condemnation=20
of <A =
href=3D"http://www.globalizationinstitute.org/blog/000330.php">subsidised=
=20
sugar</A> only a week later?</P><A name=3Dmore></A>Posted by <A=20
href=3D"mailto:jimgleeson@gmail.com">Jim</A> at 09:20 PM | <A=20
href=3D"http://blog.ctrlbreak.co.uk/archives/000312.html">Permanent =
link</A> | <A=20
onclick=3D"OpenComments(this.href); return false"=20
href=3D"http://blog.ctrlbreak.co.uk/mt-comments.cgi?entry_id=3D312">Comme=
nts (2)</A>=20
| <A onclick=3D"OpenTrackback(this.href); return false"=20
href=3D"http://blog.ctrlbreak.co.uk/mt-tb.cgi?__mode=3Dview&amp;entry_id=3D=
312">TrackBack</A>=20

<P></P></DIV>
<DIV class=3Dcontent><B><A name=3Dcomments>Comments</A></B>
<P>
